{"title_page": "Chuck E. Cheese", "text_new": "{{short description|American pizza restaurant and entertainment center chain}}\n{{Infobox company\n| logo = ChuckECheese Logo.svg\n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of CEC Entertainment, Inc.\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1977|5|17}}<br />[[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]], U.S.\n| founder = [[Nolan Bushnell]]\n| former_name = Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre<br />Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza\n| hq_location_city = [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], [[Texas]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| locations = 612 (2019)\n| area_served = [[North America]], [[South America]], [[Middle East]], [[Asia]]\n| industry = Family entertainment centers, [[fast food]]\n| key_people = Gene Landrum (first president and COO)\n| products = [[Pizza]], [[arcade game]]s, [[kiddie rides]], [[Birthday party|birthday parties]]\n| parent = Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. (1977&ndash;1984)<br />[[ShowBiz Pizza Place|ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc.]] (1984&ndash;1998)<br />CEC Entertainment, Inc. (1998&ndash;present)\n| owner = [[Apollo Global Management]]\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.chuckecheese.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chuck E. Cheese''' (formerly known as '''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre''', '''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza''', and '''Chuck E. Cheese's''') is a chain of American [[family entertainment center]]s and restaurants. The chain is the primary brand of CEC Entertainment, Inc. and is headquartered in [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], [[Texas]].<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite press release|title=CEC Entertainment, Inc. Reports Financial Results for the 2017 First Quarter|publisher=PR Newswire|date=2017-05-08|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cec-entertainment-inc-reports-financial-results-for-the-2017-first-quarter-300453621.html|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref><ref name=\"investor\">{{cite web|title=Investor Relations|work=Chuck E. Cheese official site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc.|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=72589&p=irol-irhome|format=PHP|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> The establishment serves [[pizza]] and other menu items, complemented by [[arcade game]]s, [[amusement ride]]s, and [[animatronics|animatronic]] displays as a focus of family entertainment.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> The brand took its name from its main animatronic character and mascot [[Chuck E. Cheese (character)|Chuck E. Cheese]], a comedic rat who sang and interacted with guests. It is widely understood that the character's middle initial stood for \"Entitlement.\" <ref name=infoworld>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ej0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8 |page=8 |title=Rat dishes up pizza, computerized entertainment |last=Mace |first=Scott |magazine=Infoworld |date=December 21, 1981 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Game Over: How Nintendo Conquered the World |publisher=GamePress |date=1999 |first=David |last=Sheff |page=115 |isbn=9780966961706 |quote=Above the receptionist's desk was the smiling face of Chuck E. Cheese, the company's mascot\u2014a rat.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=[[Financial World]] |title=A Noisy Decline |last=Taub |first=Stephen |pages=40\u201343 |date=November 30, 1983 |volume=152 |quote=The star of the show is a feisty-looking rat named Chuck E. Cheese, who Bushnell hopes will become as big a celebrity as Mickey Mouse.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The First Quarter: A 25-Year History of Video Games |last=Kent |first=Steven L. |date=2000 |publisher=BWD Press |isbn=9780970475503 |page=97 |quote=Bushnell called his new venture Pizza Time Theaters. He named his restaurants Chuck E. Cheese after the robotic rat mascot.}}</ref><ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Entertainment|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/entertainment.php|work=Chuck E. Cheese official site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701200748/http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/entertainment.php|archive-date=2009-07-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first location opened in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]], as Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre, on May 17, 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/ptt/ptt_ad_1977winchester.pdf|title=1977 Pizza Time Theatre Grand Opening Ad - Original Winchester Location|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bizbeatblog.dallasnews.com/2012/08/chuck-e-cheeses-founder-speaks-to-mom-in-campaign-from-dallas-richards-group.html/|title=Chuck E. Cheese's 'founder' speaks to mom in campaign from Dallas' Richards Group|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=2012-08-16|access-date=2016-08-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824000743/http://bizbeatblog.dallasnews.com/2012/08/chuck-e-cheeses-founder-speaks-to-mom-in-campaign-from-dallas-richards-group.html/|archive-date=2012-08-24|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_19540954|title=Chuck E. Cheese fined for violating child-labor laws|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=2011-12-13|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/chuck-e-cheeses-kicks-off-40-years-of-fun-celebration-300392071.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's\u00ae Kicks off '40 Years of Fun' Celebration|work=[[PR Newswire]]|date=2017-01-17|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> The concept was created by [[Atari]] co-founder [[Nolan Bushnell]], credited with bringing video games such as ''[[Pong]]'' to the mainstream. The Pizza Time Theatre was the first [[family restaurant]] to integrate food, animated entertainment, and an indoor arcade.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> Following a filing for bankruptcy, the chain was acquired by competitor [[ShowBiz Pizza Place]] in 1984, forming ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc.<ref name=\"history\"/> In 1990, the company began unifying the two brands with the goal of renaming every location to Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza.<ref name=\"cu\">{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Milford|title =ShowBiz Parent Merges Concepts Into One Big Pie|newspaper=Nation's Restaurant News|pages=12\u20133|date=1990-09-10|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|title=www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|work=ShowbizPizza.com|date=1990-09-10|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref> The logo was redesigned in 1994 after ''pizza'' was dropped from each store's name.<ref name=\"history\"/> ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc. became CEC Entertainment, Inc. in 1998, and over 600 Chuck E. Cheese stores are open in 47 states and 17 countries {{as of|2019|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"financial\"/><ref name=\"investor\"/>\n\n==Chain history==\n[[File:Cec-pizzagames.png|thumb|260px|Logo until 2018\u20132019]]\n===Foundation===\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese blue tube.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Two children in the Ticket Blaster. This is used whenever a child has a birthday party. The birthday child collects as many tickets as they can before time expires.]]\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese Adventure! Skytubes.jpg|thumb|left|150px|A girl playing in the now removed SkyTubes play area.]]\nChuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre was founded by [[Atari]] founder [[Nolan Bushnell]], who was seeking to expand the purview of video game arcades beyond more adult locations like pool halls to a child- and family-friendly venue.<ref name=\"fsm\">{{cite news|last=Packer|first=Linda|title=Catering To Kids|newspaper=Food Service Marketing|pages=46\u201347|date=October 1979|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/ptt_79fsm.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>Kent, Steve L. ''The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pok\u00e9mon and Beyond: The Story behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World''. Roseville, CA: Prima Pub., 2001.</ref> Bushnell's experience in the amusement park industry, as well as his fondness for [[the Walt Disney Company]], were influential in the conceptualization of the Pizza Time Theatre concept.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Pizza Time's Vaudeville Theatre|newspaper=Western Foodservice|date=March 1979|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/ptt_79foodservice.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The first location opened in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], California, in 1977, and was labeled as the first family restaurant to integrate food, cheap animated entertainment, and an indoor arcade.<ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref name=\"history\"/> In 1978, Bushnell purchased the Pizza Time Theatre concept from Atari's then-corporate parent, [[Time Warner|Warner Communications]].<ref name=\"brock\">{{Cite news|last=Kinkead|first=Gwen|title=High Profits from a Weird Pizza Combination|newspaper=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|pages=62\u201368|date=July 1982|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_82fortune.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> Gene Landrum then resigned from Atari and was made President and Chief Operating Officer of Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre.<ref>''Atari Inc: Business is Fun''; Marty Goldberg, Curt Vendel; Syzygy Press, 2012; pp. 325\u2013334</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ponder|first=Erica|title=Building a Strong Business Network with Dr. Gene Landrum|url=http://stylemagazine.com/news/2015/jun/04/building-strong-business-network-dr-gene-landrum/|website=Houston Style Magazine|access-date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nBushnell has said of his decision to open a pizza restaurant, \"It was my pet project&nbsp;... I chose pizza because of the wait time and the build schedule: very few components and not too many ways to screw it up.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/07/chuck-e-cheeses-silicon-valley-startup-the-origins-of-the-best-pizza-chain-ever/277869/|title=Chuck E. Cheese's, Silicon Valley Startup: The Origins of the Best Pizza Chain Ever|date=July 17, 2013|access-date=January 26, 2017|magazine=The Atlantic|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.}}</ref> After finding out from employees working on the animatronics that the costume he bought was a rodent rather than the coyote he thought he was buying, Bushnell says he suggested changing the name of the establishment from the planned \"Coyote Pizza\" to \"Rick Rat's Pizza\". Marketing people disliked that and proposed \"Chuck E. Cheese\" instead, which is what was used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stitcher.com/podcast/national-public-radio/how-i-built-this/e/atari-chuck-e-cheeses-nolan-bushnell-49269472|title=How I Built This / Atari & Chuck E. Cheese's: Nolan Bushnell}}</ref>\n\nTo expand beyond California and the west coast, Nolan began to franchise, resulting in a co-development agreement between himself and [[Robert L. Brock|Robert Brock]] of Topeka Inn Management in 1979. The agreement handed Brock exclusive franchising rights for opening Pizza Time Theatres in sixteen states across the Southern and Midwestern United States,<ref name=\"brock\"/> while also forming a company subdivision, \"Pizza Show Biz\", to develop the Pizza Time Theatres.<ref name=\"brock\"/>\n\n===ShowBiz Pizza Place ===\n{{main|ShowBiz Pizza Place}}\nIn November 1979, Brock met [[Aaron Fechter]] of [[Creative Engineering, Inc.]] Concerned that Fechter's animatronics would be too strong a competition for Bushnell's work, Brock requested that Bushnell release him from the co-development agreement, citing misrepresentation.<ref name=\"brock\"/> In December 1979, Brock and Fechter formed \"Showbiz Pizza Place Inc\", severing Brock's business relationship with Bushnell.<ref name=\"brock\"/><ref>{{cite press release|title=Rock-afire Explosion Brochure|publisher=Creative Engineering, Inc|year=1980|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/cei/cei_rockafire.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> [[ShowBiz Pizza Place]] was conceptually identical to Pizza Time Theatre in all aspects except for animation, which would be provided by Creative Engineering.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Showbiz Pizza Place opened its first location on March 3, 1980, in Kansas City, Missouri.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nUpon the opening of ShowBiz Pizza Place, Bushnell sued Brock and Topeka Inn Management over breach of contract.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Brock immediately issued a counter-suit against Bushnell, citing misrepresentation.<ref name=\"brock\"/> The court case began in March 1980, eventually settling out of court with Showbiz agreeing to pay Pizza Time Theatre a portion of its profits over the following decade.<ref name=\"brock\"/> During this period, Topeka Inn Management also changed its name to Brock Hotel Corporation and moved its headquarters to [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], Texas.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Both restaurants experienced increased success as the video game industry became more robust,<ref name=\"brock\"/> and, to maintain competition, both franchises continually modified and diversified their animatronic shows.\n\n===Mergers and restructuring===\n[[File:Chuck E Cheese's Pizza (crop).jpg|thumb|right|An older Chuck E. Cheese facility under the now defunct title of \"Chuck E Cheese's Pizza\".]]\nIn 1981, Pizza Time Theatre went public; however, the evolving video game industry and the [[North American video game crash of 1983|video game crash of 1983]] resulted in significant losses for Pizza Time Theatre, which lost $15 million in 1983, and by 1984, Bushnell's debts were insurmountable, resulting in the filing of [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] for Pizza Time Theatre Inc.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|title=Company History|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/company-info/history.php|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-04|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106075723/http://www.chuckecheese.com/company-info/history.php|archive-date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> Showbiz then bought the foundering company, recreating itself as Showbiz Pizza Time Inc.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nAfter the merger, both restaurant chains continued operating under their respective titles, while major financial restructuring had begun.<ref name=\"history\"/> During this period, Creative Engineering began to sever ties with ShowBiz Pizza Time (officially splitting in September 1990), resulting in the unification of the two brands. By 1992, all restaurants assumed the name of ''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza''.<ref name=\"cu\"/> The name was then shortened to ''Chuck E. Cheese's'' by March 1995 after a redesigned concept.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/813920/0000813920-95-000002.txt|title=1994 FORM 10-K|work=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|date=2009|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref> In 1998, Showbiz Pizza Time renamed itself CEC Entertainment, Inc. to reflect the remaining chain brand.<ref name=\"investor\"/><ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n===International expansion===\n\nIn the early 1980s, the restaurant franchise debuted in Australia under the name Charlie Cheese's Pizza Playhouse. The name change had to do with the common meaning of the word \"chuck\", which in Australia is a reference to the phrase \"to throw up\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Collectables|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/ceccollect/related/|website=showbizpizza.com|access-date=2016-02-21|last=VegaNova}}</ref> Consecutively, Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. also opened at least one restaurant in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Singapore]], which both closed shortly thereafter as a result of the initial company's 1984 bankruptcy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:CEC Marina Arauco Vi\u00f1a del Mar.jpg|thumb|right|Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Boulevard Marina, [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar]]- Chile.]]\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Mall Aventura Plaza Trujillo.jpg|thumb|right|Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Mallplaza, [[Trujillo, Peru|Trujillo]]- Per\u00fa.]]\n\nA franchise store was opened in a suburb of Paris, France at the time Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. filed for bankruptcy. Chuck E. Cheese's was about to open in the [[United Kingdom]], but somehow pulled out.\n\nInternational markets:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chuckecheese.com/locations/?type=2&val=SK&miles=20|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Locations Near You|publisher=Chuck E. Cheese|access-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1%;\" |#\n! style=\"width:20%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:15%;\" data-sort-type=\"date\"|Date of first store\n! style=\"width:20%;\" |First outlet location\n! style=\"width:10%;\" data-sort-type=\"number\" |Number of currently operating outlets\n|-\n! 1\n| United States\n| May 17, 1977\n| San Jose, California\n| 527\n|-\n! 2\n| Canada\n| 1981\n| Burlington, Ontario\n| 10\n|-\n! 3\n| Puerto Rico\n| 1983\n| San Juan\n| 3\n|-\n! 4\n| Guatemala\n| 1986\n| Guatemala City\n| 2\n|-\n! 5\n| Chile\n| 1993\n| Santiago\n| 9\n|-\n! 6\n| Saudi Arabia\n| December 2001\n| Jeddah\n| 17\n|-\n! 7\n| United Arab Emirates\n| 2006\n| Dubai\n| 3\n|-\n! 8\n| Guam\n| 2010\n| Tamuning\n| 1\n|-\n! 9\n| Mexico\n| 2012\n| Monterrey, Nuevo Leon\n| 19\n|-\n! 10\n| Peru\n| 2013\n| Lima (Plaza Norte)\n| 7\n|-\n! 11\n| Panama\n| 2014\n| Panama City\n| 2\n|-\n! 12\n| Trinidad and Tobago\n| 2014\n| Montrose\n| 2\n|-\n! 13\n| Colombia\n| 2015\n| Bogota\n| 2\n|-\n! 14\n| Honduras\n| May 2017\n| Tegucigalpa\n| 3\n|-\n! 15\n| Costa Rica\n| April 2018\n| San Jos\u00e9\n| 1\n|-\n! 16\n| Jordan\n| September 2019\n| Amman\n| 1\n|-\n! 17\n| India\n| December 2019\n| Mumbai\n| 1\n|}\n\n\nThe company was supposed to open a branch in the Philippines at [[Glorietta]] but it was scrapped due to the discrepancies in the mall's design which standards of CEC locations must be followed. The location of the first branch is still being proposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/01/29/14/what-happened-ph-opening-chuck-e-cheese|title=What happened to PH opening of Chuck E. Cheese?|publisher=ABS-CBN News|access-date=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Buyout and modern redesign===\nBy 2012, CEC was struggling with decreasing revenue.<ref>https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2012/02/23/chuck-e-cheese-s-parent-boosts-its-per-share-profit/</ref> They ran a rebranding campaign, changing the rat mascot into a rock star guitar-playing mouse.<ref name=\"AP 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/chuck-e-cheese-being-replaced-hipper-image-165852270--finance.html |title=Chuck E. Cheese being replaced with hipper image |author=Candice Choi |date=July 3, 2012 |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Yahoo! News |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> In-store restaurant sales continued to decline through 2013 but merchandising and box office revenue increased.<ref>https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/11/09/is-chuck-e-cheese-still-a-rock-star.aspx</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, [[Apollo Global Management]] acquired CEC Entertainment, Inc. for $54 per share, or about $950 million.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/chuck-cheese-owner-agrees-9504m-buyout-21553287 Chuck E. Cheese Owner Agrees to $950M Buyout]; ABC News; January 16, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/apollo-global-management-announces-completion-of-its-acquisition-of-cec-entertainment-inc-2014-02-14 Apollo Global Management Announces Completion of Its Acquisition of CEC Entertainment, Inc.]; BusinessWire - Press release; February 14, 2014</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, under [[Apollo Global Management]], CEC Entertainment announced that they would purchase their Phoenix-based competitor, [[Peter Piper Pizza]] from ACON Investments.<ref>[http://aconinvestments.com/chuck-e-cheeses-announces-acquisition-peter-piper-pizza/ Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Announces Acquisition of Peter Piper Pizza]; Acon Investments; October 16, 2014</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the company began to pilot a new design concept at seven remodeled locations (three in [[Kansas City]], three in [[San Antonio]], one in [[Selma, Texas]]), branded as Chuck E. Cheese Pizzeria & Games. These locations feature more upscale decor with a \"muted\" interior color scheme, an open kitchen, the \"Play Pass\" card system to replace arcade tokens, and the animatronic stage show replaced by a dance floor area. These changes, along with expansions to food offerings, are intended to help the chain provide an experience that can appeal better to adult visitors, and encourage family dining as opposed to primarily parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-chuck-e-cheese-band-breakup-0824-biz-20170823-story.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's breaking up the (animatronic) band|last=Channick|first=Robert|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/09/chuck-e-cheeses-is-getting-a-major-redesign.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's is getting a major redesign|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|work=[[CNBC]]|date=2017-08-09|access-date=2017-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the corporation announced it would go public on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] through a shell company, Leo Holdings Corporation, in which Apollo will still own 51% of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/casual-dining/chuck-e-cheese-s-plans-merger-public-trading|last=Ruggless|first=Ron|date=April 8, 2019|title=Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s plans merger, public trading|work=[[Nation's Restaurant News]]|access-date=Apr 9, 2019}}</ref> ''Bloomberg''  also reported that after going public, Chuck E. Cheese would no longer have animatronic animals as part of the entertainment.<ref name=\"Bloomberg2019\">https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-08/animatronic-animals-won-t-be-part-of-the-public-chuck-e-cheese?srnd=premium</ref> The proposed merger between CEC Entertainment and LEO Holdings Corporation has been terminated as of July 29, 2019.\n\n==Menu items==\nWhile its primary focus is pizza, Chuck E. Cheese also offers [[Lunch meat|cold-cut]] sandwiches, chicken wings, [[salad bar]]s, appetizers, platters, and desserts. Some stores are also used as test locations which feature new Chuck E. Cheese foods.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nutritional Information|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/menu/nutritional-information.pdf|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PDF|date=January 2009|access-date=2009-05-13}}</ref> Certain Chuck E. Cheese locations also offer beer and wine.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lieberman|first1=Al|last2=Esgate|first2=Patricia|title=The Entertainment Marketing Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ROXOZCJa1kC&pg=PT297|format=PDF|access-date=2009-05-13|edition=Illustrated|year=2002|publisher=FT Press|isbn=0-13-029350-4|page=272|chapter=Location-Based Entertainment and Experiential Branding|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ROXOZCJa1kC&pg=PT297&lr=#PPT294,M1|last-author-amp=yes}}</ref>\n\nStarting on November 13, 2012, new gluten-free menu items were available at more than 500 locations in the U.S. and Canada. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/new-glutenfree-offerings|title=New Gluten-Free Offerings - Chuck E. Cheese's|work=Chuck E. Cheese}}</ref>\n\n==Arcade and currency==\n\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese (4328479524).jpg|thumb|right|140px|A 2001 Chuck E. Cheese token.]]\nFrom the time of the company's inception to today, one of the main draws for the stores has been the [[Video arcade|arcade]].<ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref name=\"investor\"/> The arcade games primarily consist of either [[redemption game]]s or [[Arcade game|video arcade games]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Games & Rides|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/games-rides.php|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\nThe brass [[Token coin|tokens]] issued by the company for use in their arcades exist in numerous varieties, and are collected by [[exonumia]] enthusiasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chuck E. Cheese Tokens|work=Forrest's Token Page|url=http://users.pullman.com/fjstevens/tokens/cec/CEC.html|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>  The company once tested a card access method for use with their arcade and skill games in one location. The test location would no longer use tokens, and instead use a refillable card to access credits, which replace tokens, and points, which replace tickets. However, this was later scrapped. It was tested under different names, including \"Chuck E.'s Super Discount Card\" and \"Chuck E. Token Card\".<ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=CEC Token Cards|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/tokens/cards/index.html|format=CSS|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=Super Discount Card Poster 9Irving, TX 2006)|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/cec/tx_irving_cv3/03.jpg|format=JPG|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref>\nThis method is currently being tested in some markets again. Instead of electronic tickets like the former cards, patrons still carry paper tickets, and the card just takes the place of the metal tokens. CECE, or CEC Entertainment, has called the new system \"Play Pass\".\n\n==Characters==\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese animatronic, Laguna Hills, CA.jpg |thumb |right |Chuck E. Cheese animatronic, with \"Pizza Time\" clock, in 2017.]]\n\nAlong with the arcade, the other main draw for the centers since the beginning was its animatronic show.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loftus |first1=Jamie |title=A History of Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Animatronic Band |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kkn7y/a-history-of-chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band |website=Vice |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> However, there are now several different styles of animatronic shows in use within the company, depending on when the location opened, whether it was renovated, and other factors.<ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=Pizza Time Theatre: Stage Shows|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/ptp/stages/index.html|format=CSS|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>\n\nWhen the first location opened in 1977, the animatronic characters were featured in framed portraits hanging on the walls of the main dining area, but they are no longer in use today. The original show featured Crusty The Cat (the first character to face retirement as he was soon replaced with Mr. Munch in 1978), Pasqually the singing chef, Jasper T. Jowls, the Warblettes, and the main focus of the show, Chuck E. Cheese.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Program|publisher=[[Atari]]|year=1977|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/ptt/ptt_77menu.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> In the early 90s, when the franchise unified Chuck E. Cheese with ShowBiz Pizza, the animatronics used for [[the Rock-afire Explosion]] band were redressed as \"Munch's Make Believe Band\", with Chuck E., Jasper, Helen Henny, Munch, and Pasqually costumes replacing the Rock-afire characters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Loftus |first1=Jamie |title=A History of Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Animatronic Band |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kkn7y/a-history-of-chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Vice |date=August 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater, restaurants also added \"Cabaret\" shows in separate rooms of each restaurant.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> One of the early Cabaret characters was Dolli Dimples, a hippopotamus who played the piano and sang in the blues/jazz style of performer [[Pearl Bailey]].<ref name=infoworld/>\n\nThe in-house control system consisted of a [[MOS Technology 6502|6502]]-based controller in a card cage with various driver boards was called \"Cyberamics\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Balcony Show Photograph #1|year=1981|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/ptt/fl_brandon/10.jpg|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Balcony Show Photograph #2|date=1980s|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/ptt/nm_unknown/05.jpg|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1998, the company's show installed into new stores, referred to as \"Studio C\", consisted of a single animated Chuck E. Cheese character created by [[Garner Holt]] alongside large television monitors, lighting effects, and interactive elements.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Chuck E.'s New Look|publisher=Garner Holt Productions|year=1998|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/cec_98studioc.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> The other characters appear as puppets on the TV screens. The control system dubbed \"Cyberstar\" was re-designed from the ground up and produced by Dave Philipsen. In some markets, the company has also tried a new store concept that omits the animated show entirely. This is the Circle of Lights stage which either consists of a live Chuck E. Cheese costume character or an animatronic in a futuristic light stage with large television monitors. \n\nIn July 2012, the longstanding rat mascot was rebranded, changing to a slimmer rock star mouse who plays electric guitar. Voice actor [[Duncan Brannan]], who for 19 years had characterized Chuck E. Cheese as a wise-cracking rat from New Jersey, was replaced with [[Jaret Reddick]], the frontman and guitarist for the pop punk band [[Bowling for Soup]].<ref name=\"AP 2012\"/><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chuck-e-cheese-makeover-duncan-brannan-jaret-reddick-344677</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the chain announced that animatronic shows would be removed in favor of a modernized dance floor. The move was piloted in a handful of locations prior to being implemented company-wide.<ref name=\"AnimatronicRemoval\">{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Jennings|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Animatronic Band Is Starting to Break Up and Fans Are Heartbroken|url=https://gizmodo.com/chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band-is-starting-to-break-1797875869|access-date=18 August 2017|work=GizModo|publisher=GizModo|date=17 August 2017}}</ref> <ref name=\"AnimatronicRemoval\" /> The characters were removed from all chains in November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chuck E. Cheese unveils new restaurant design, gets rid of tokens |url=https://abc7chicago.com/business/chuck-e-cheese-unveils-new-restaurant-design/5691942/ |accessdate=5 March 2020 |publisher=ABC7 Chicago |date=Nov 12, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:CEC 32.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Chuck E. Cheese [[walkaround character]] performing in 2017.]]\n\n===Costumed shows===\nTwo types of costumed shows are used by Chuck E. Cheese: the Live show and the Road show. The Live show is performed at the front of the stage in the showroom, whenever a child is celebrating a birthday. In the live show a customized rendition of \"Happy Birthday\" is sung to the child that is celebrating the birthday. A costumed Chuck E. Cheese dances with the guests and sings, while being accompanied by the cast members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Birthday Parties|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc.|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/parties/birthday.php|format=PHP|access-date=2009-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228204107/http://www.chuckecheese.com/parties/birthday.php|archive-date=2009-02-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Road show is a performance by a costumed Chuck E. Cheese character, and is performed outside the normal showroom. Children are gathered via the public announcement system or by Chuck E. Cheese himself.  The children must dance in order to win free tickets. The free tickets are thrown at the end of the performance for all the children that participated. Chuck comes out every hour on the half hour. The songs that he and the children dance to are usually well-known classic songs such as \"[[If You're Happy and You Know It]]\" and \"[[Head, Shoulders, Knees, and Toes]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chuck E. Cheeses}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.chuckecheese.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Food}}\n{{Pizza chains|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Irving, Texas]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of Canada]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pizza franchises]]\n[[Category:Video arcades]]\n[[Category:Fictional mice and rats]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1984]]\n[[Category:Theme restaurants]]\n[[Category:Animatronic attractions]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1980s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Fast-food franchises]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1977]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Apollo Global Management companies]]\n[[Category:1977 in robotics]]\n[[Category:Atari]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pizza restaurant and entertainment center chain}}\n{{Infobox company\n| logo = ChuckECheese Logo.svg\n| type = [[Subsidiary]] of CEC Entertainment, Inc.\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1977|5|17}}<br />[[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]], U.S.\n| founder = [[Nolan Bushnell]]\n| former_name = Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre<br />Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza\n| hq_location_city = [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], [[Texas]]\n| hq_location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n| locations = 612 (2019)\n| area_served = [[North America]], [[South America]], [[Middle East]], [[Asia]]\n| industry = Family entertainment centers, [[fast food]]\n| key_people = Gene Landrum (first president and COO)\n| products = [[Pizza]], [[arcade game]]s, [[kiddie rides]], [[Birthday party|birthday parties]]\n| parent = Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. (1977&ndash;1984)<br />[[ShowBiz Pizza Place|ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc.]] (1984&ndash;1998)<br />CEC Entertainment, Inc. (1998&ndash;present)\n| owner = [[Apollo Global Management]]\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.chuckecheese.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Chuck E. Cheese''' (formerly known as '''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre''', '''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza''', and '''Chuck E. Cheese's''') is a chain of American [[family entertainment center]]s and restaurants. The chain is the primary brand of CEC Entertainment, Inc. and is headquartered in [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], [[Texas]].<ref name=\"financial\">{{cite press release|title=CEC Entertainment, Inc. Reports Financial Results for the 2017 First Quarter|publisher=PR Newswire|date=2017-05-08|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/cec-entertainment-inc-reports-financial-results-for-the-2017-first-quarter-300453621.html|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref><ref name=\"investor\">{{cite web|title=Investor Relations|work=Chuck E. Cheese official site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc.|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=72589&p=irol-irhome|format=PHP|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> The establishment serves [[pizza]] and other menu items, complemented by [[arcade game]]s, [[amusement ride]]s, and [[animatronics|animatronic]] displays as a focus of family entertainment.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> The brand took its name from its main animatronic character and mascot [[Chuck E. Cheese (character)|Chuck E. Cheese]], a comedic rat who sang and interacted with guests.<ref name=infoworld>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ej0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA8 |page=8 |title=Rat dishes up pizza, computerized entertainment |last=Mace |first=Scott |magazine=Infoworld |date=December 21, 1981 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Game Over: How Nintendo Conquered the World |publisher=GamePress |date=1999 |first=David |last=Sheff |page=115 |isbn=9780966961706 |quote=Above the receptionist's desk was the smiling face of Chuck E. Cheese, the company's mascot\u2014a rat.}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=[[Financial World]] |title=A Noisy Decline |last=Taub |first=Stephen |pages=40\u201343 |date=November 30, 1983 |volume=152 |quote=The star of the show is a feisty-looking rat named Chuck E. Cheese, who Bushnell hopes will become as big a celebrity as Mickey Mouse.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The First Quarter: A 25-Year History of Video Games |last=Kent |first=Steven L. |date=2000 |publisher=BWD Press |isbn=9780970475503 |page=97 |quote=Bushnell called his new venture Pizza Time Theaters. He named his restaurants Chuck E. Cheese after the robotic rat mascot.}}</ref><ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Entertainment|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/entertainment.php|work=Chuck E. Cheese official site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701200748/http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/entertainment.php|archive-date=2009-07-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first location opened in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], [[California]], as Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre, on May 17, 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/ptt/ptt_ad_1977winchester.pdf|title=1977 Pizza Time Theatre Grand Opening Ad - Original Winchester Location|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bizbeatblog.dallasnews.com/2012/08/chuck-e-cheeses-founder-speaks-to-mom-in-campaign-from-dallas-richards-group.html/|title=Chuck E. Cheese's 'founder' speaks to mom in campaign from Dallas' Richards Group|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=2012-08-16|access-date=2016-08-20|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824000743/http://bizbeatblog.dallasnews.com/2012/08/chuck-e-cheeses-founder-speaks-to-mom-in-campaign-from-dallas-richards-group.html/|archive-date=2012-08-24|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_19540954|title=Chuck E. Cheese fined for violating child-labor laws|work=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=2011-12-13|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/chuck-e-cheeses-kicks-off-40-years-of-fun-celebration-300392071.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's\u00ae Kicks off '40 Years of Fun' Celebration|work=[[PR Newswire]]|date=2017-01-17|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> The concept was created by [[Atari]] co-founder [[Nolan Bushnell]], credited with bringing video games such as ''[[Pong]]'' to the mainstream. The Pizza Time Theatre was the first [[family restaurant]] to integrate food, animated entertainment, and an indoor arcade.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> Following a filing for bankruptcy, the chain was acquired by competitor [[ShowBiz Pizza Place]] in 1984, forming ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc.<ref name=\"history\"/> In 1990, the company began unifying the two brands with the goal of renaming every location to Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza.<ref name=\"cu\">{{Cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Milford|title =ShowBiz Parent Merges Concepts Into One Big Pie|newspaper=Nation's Restaurant News|pages=12\u20133|date=1990-09-10|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|title=www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_cuarticle.pdf|work=ShowbizPizza.com|date=1990-09-10|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref> The logo was redesigned in 1994 after ''pizza'' was dropped from each store's name.<ref name=\"history\"/> ShowBiz Pizza Time, Inc. became CEC Entertainment, Inc. in 1998, and over 600 Chuck E. Cheese stores are open in 47 states and 17 countries {{as of|2019|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"financial\"/><ref name=\"investor\"/>\n\n==Chain history==\n[[File:Cec-pizzagames.png|thumb|260px|Logo until 2018\u20132019]]\n===Foundation===\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese blue tube.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Two children in the Ticket Blaster. This is used whenever a child has a birthday party. The birthday child collects as many tickets as they can before time expires.]]\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese Adventure! Skytubes.jpg|thumb|left|150px|A girl playing in the now removed SkyTubes play area.]]\nChuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre was founded by [[Atari]] founder [[Nolan Bushnell]], who was seeking to expand the purview of video game arcades beyond more adult locations like pool halls to a child- and family-friendly venue.<ref name=\"fsm\">{{cite news|last=Packer|first=Linda|title=Catering To Kids|newspaper=Food Service Marketing|pages=46\u201347|date=October 1979|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/ptt_79fsm.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>Kent, Steve L. ''The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pok\u00e9mon and Beyond: The Story behind the Craze That Touched Our Lives and Changed the World''. Roseville, CA: Prima Pub., 2001.</ref> Bushnell's experience in the amusement park industry, as well as his fondness for [[the Walt Disney Company]], were influential in the conceptualization of the Pizza Time Theatre concept.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Pizza Time's Vaudeville Theatre|newspaper=Western Foodservice|date=March 1979|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/ptt_79foodservice.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> The first location opened in [[San Jose, California|San Jose]], California, in 1977, and was labeled as the first family restaurant to integrate food, cheap animated entertainment, and an indoor arcade.<ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref name=\"history\"/> In 1978, Bushnell purchased the Pizza Time Theatre concept from Atari's then-corporate parent, [[Time Warner|Warner Communications]].<ref name=\"brock\">{{Cite news|last=Kinkead|first=Gwen|title=High Profits from a Weird Pizza Combination|newspaper=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|pages=62\u201368|date=July 1982|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/joint/joint_82fortune.pdf|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> Gene Landrum then resigned from Atari and was made President and Chief Operating Officer of Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza Time Theatre.<ref>''Atari Inc: Business is Fun''; Marty Goldberg, Curt Vendel; Syzygy Press, 2012; pp. 325\u2013334</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ponder|first=Erica|title=Building a Strong Business Network with Dr. Gene Landrum|url=http://stylemagazine.com/news/2015/jun/04/building-strong-business-network-dr-gene-landrum/|website=Houston Style Magazine|access-date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nBushnell has said of his decision to open a pizza restaurant, \"It was my pet project&nbsp;... I chose pizza because of the wait time and the build schedule: very few components and not too many ways to screw it up.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2013/07/chuck-e-cheeses-silicon-valley-startup-the-origins-of-the-best-pizza-chain-ever/277869/|title=Chuck E. Cheese's, Silicon Valley Startup: The Origins of the Best Pizza Chain Ever|date=July 17, 2013|access-date=January 26, 2017|magazine=The Atlantic|last=Madrigal|first=Alexis C.}}</ref> After finding out from employees working on the animatronics that the costume he bought was a rodent rather than the coyote he thought he was buying, Bushnell says he suggested changing the name of the establishment from the planned \"Coyote Pizza\" to \"Rick Rat's Pizza\". Marketing people disliked that and proposed \"Chuck E. Cheese\" instead, which is what was used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stitcher.com/podcast/national-public-radio/how-i-built-this/e/atari-chuck-e-cheeses-nolan-bushnell-49269472|title=How I Built This / Atari & Chuck E. Cheese's: Nolan Bushnell}}</ref>\n\nTo expand beyond California and the west coast, Nolan began to franchise, resulting in a co-development agreement between himself and [[Robert L. Brock|Robert Brock]] of Topeka Inn Management in 1979. The agreement handed Brock exclusive franchising rights for opening Pizza Time Theatres in sixteen states across the Southern and Midwestern United States,<ref name=\"brock\"/> while also forming a company subdivision, \"Pizza Show Biz\", to develop the Pizza Time Theatres.<ref name=\"brock\"/>\n\n===ShowBiz Pizza Place ===\n{{main|ShowBiz Pizza Place}}\nIn November 1979, Brock met [[Aaron Fechter]] of [[Creative Engineering, Inc.]] Concerned that Fechter's animatronics would be too strong a competition for Bushnell's work, Brock requested that Bushnell release him from the co-development agreement, citing misrepresentation.<ref name=\"brock\"/> In December 1979, Brock and Fechter formed \"Showbiz Pizza Place Inc\", severing Brock's business relationship with Bushnell.<ref name=\"brock\"/><ref>{{cite press release|title=Rock-afire Explosion Brochure|publisher=Creative Engineering, Inc|year=1980|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/cei/cei_rockafire.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> [[ShowBiz Pizza Place]] was conceptually identical to Pizza Time Theatre in all aspects except for animation, which would be provided by Creative Engineering.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Showbiz Pizza Place opened its first location on March 3, 1980, in Kansas City, Missouri.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nUpon the opening of ShowBiz Pizza Place, Bushnell sued Brock and Topeka Inn Management over breach of contract.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Brock immediately issued a counter-suit against Bushnell, citing misrepresentation.<ref name=\"brock\"/> The court case began in March 1980, eventually settling out of court with Showbiz agreeing to pay Pizza Time Theatre a portion of its profits over the following decade.<ref name=\"brock\"/> During this period, Topeka Inn Management also changed its name to Brock Hotel Corporation and moved its headquarters to [[Irving, Texas|Irving]], Texas.<ref name=\"brock\"/> Both restaurants experienced increased success as the video game industry became more robust,<ref name=\"brock\"/> and, to maintain competition, both franchises continually modified and diversified their animatronic shows.\n\n===Mergers and restructuring===\n[[File:Chuck E Cheese's Pizza (crop).jpg|thumb|right|An older Chuck E. Cheese facility under the now defunct title of \"Chuck E Cheese's Pizza\".]]\nIn 1981, Pizza Time Theatre went public; however, the evolving video game industry and the [[North American video game crash of 1983|video game crash of 1983]] resulted in significant losses for Pizza Time Theatre, which lost $15 million in 1983, and by 1984, Bushnell's debts were insurmountable, resulting in the filing of [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 11 bankruptcy]] for Pizza Time Theatre Inc.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|title=Company History|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/company-info/history.php|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-04|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106075723/http://www.chuckecheese.com/company-info/history.php|archive-date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> Showbiz then bought the foundering company, recreating itself as Showbiz Pizza Time Inc.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nAfter the merger, both restaurant chains continued operating under their respective titles, while major financial restructuring had begun.<ref name=\"history\"/> During this period, Creative Engineering began to sever ties with ShowBiz Pizza Time (officially splitting in September 1990), resulting in the unification of the two brands. By 1992, all restaurants assumed the name of ''Chuck E. Cheese's Pizza''.<ref name=\"cu\"/> The name was then shortened to ''Chuck E. Cheese's'' by March 1995 after a redesigned concept.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/813920/0000813920-95-000002.txt|title=1994 FORM 10-K|work=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|date=2009|access-date=2016-08-20}}</ref> In 1998, Showbiz Pizza Time renamed itself CEC Entertainment, Inc. to reflect the remaining chain brand.<ref name=\"investor\"/><ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n===International expansion===\n\nIn the early 1980s, the restaurant franchise debuted in Australia under the name Charlie Cheese's Pizza Playhouse. The name change had to do with the common meaning of the word \"chuck\", which in Australia is a reference to the phrase \"to throw up\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Collectables|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/ceccollect/related/|website=showbizpizza.com|access-date=2016-02-21|last=VegaNova}}</ref> Consecutively, Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. also opened at least one restaurant in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Singapore]], which both closed shortly thereafter as a result of the initial company's 1984 bankruptcy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:CEC Marina Arauco Vi\u00f1a del Mar.jpg|thumb|right|Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Boulevard Marina, [[Vi\u00f1a del Mar]]- Chile.]]\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Mall Aventura Plaza Trujillo.jpg|thumb|right|Chuck E. Cheese\u00b4s Mallplaza, [[Trujillo, Peru|Trujillo]]- Per\u00fa.]]\n\nA franchise store was opened in a suburb of Paris, France at the time Pizza Time Theatre, Inc. filed for bankruptcy. Chuck E. Cheese's was about to open in the [[United Kingdom]], but somehow pulled out.\n\nInternational markets:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chuckecheese.com/locations/?type=2&val=SK&miles=20|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Locations Near You|publisher=Chuck E. Cheese|access-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1%;\" |#\n! style=\"width:20%;\" |Country\n! style=\"width:15%;\" data-sort-type=\"date\"|Date of first store\n! style=\"width:20%;\" |First outlet location\n! style=\"width:10%;\" data-sort-type=\"number\" |Number of currently operating outlets\n|-\n! 1\n| United States\n| May 17, 1977\n| San Jose, California\n| 527\n|-\n! 2\n| Canada\n| 1981\n| Burlington, Ontario\n| 10\n|-\n! 3\n| Puerto Rico\n| 1983\n| San Juan\n| 3\n|-\n! 4\n| Guatemala\n| 1986\n| Guatemala City\n| 2\n|-\n! 5\n| Chile\n| 1993\n| Santiago\n| 9\n|-\n! 6\n| Saudi Arabia\n| December 2001\n| Jeddah\n| 17\n|-\n! 7\n| United Arab Emirates\n| 2006\n| Dubai\n| 3\n|-\n! 8\n| Guam\n| 2010\n| Tamuning\n| 1\n|-\n! 9\n| Mexico\n| 2012\n| Monterrey, Nuevo Leon\n| 19\n|-\n! 10\n| Peru\n| 2013\n| Lima (Plaza Norte)\n| 7\n|-\n! 11\n| Panama\n| 2014\n| Panama City\n| 2\n|-\n! 12\n| Trinidad and Tobago\n| 2014\n| Montrose\n| 2\n|-\n! 13\n| Colombia\n| 2015\n| Bogota\n| 2\n|-\n! 14\n| Honduras\n| May 2017\n| Tegucigalpa\n| 3\n|-\n! 15\n| Costa Rica\n| April 2018\n| San Jos\u00e9\n| 1\n|-\n! 16\n| Jordan\n| September 2019\n| Amman\n| 1\n|-\n! 17\n| India\n| December 2019\n| Mumbai\n| 1\n|}\n\n\nThe company was supposed to open a branch in the Philippines at [[Glorietta]] but it was scrapped due to the discrepancies in the mall's design which standards of CEC locations must be followed. The location of the first branch is still being proposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/lifestyle/01/29/14/what-happened-ph-opening-chuck-e-cheese|title=What happened to PH opening of Chuck E. Cheese?|publisher=ABS-CBN News|access-date=June 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Buyout and modern redesign===\nBy 2012, CEC was struggling with decreasing revenue.<ref>https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2012/02/23/chuck-e-cheese-s-parent-boosts-its-per-share-profit/</ref> They ran a rebranding campaign, changing the rat mascot into a rock star guitar-playing mouse.<ref name=\"AP 2012\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/chuck-e-cheese-being-replaced-hipper-image-165852270--finance.html |title=Chuck E. Cheese being replaced with hipper image |author=Candice Choi |date=July 3, 2012 |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=Yahoo! News |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> In-store restaurant sales continued to decline through 2013 but merchandising and box office revenue increased.<ref>https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/11/09/is-chuck-e-cheese-still-a-rock-star.aspx</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, [[Apollo Global Management]] acquired CEC Entertainment, Inc. for $54 per share, or about $950 million.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Business/wireStory/chuck-cheese-owner-agrees-9504m-buyout-21553287 Chuck E. Cheese Owner Agrees to $950M Buyout]; ABC News; January 16, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/apollo-global-management-announces-completion-of-its-acquisition-of-cec-entertainment-inc-2014-02-14 Apollo Global Management Announces Completion of Its Acquisition of CEC Entertainment, Inc.]; BusinessWire - Press release; February 14, 2014</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, under [[Apollo Global Management]], CEC Entertainment announced that they would purchase their Phoenix-based competitor, [[Peter Piper Pizza]] from ACON Investments.<ref>[http://aconinvestments.com/chuck-e-cheeses-announces-acquisition-peter-piper-pizza/ Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Announces Acquisition of Peter Piper Pizza]; Acon Investments; October 16, 2014</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the company began to pilot a new design concept at seven remodeled locations (three in [[Kansas City]], three in [[San Antonio]], one in [[Selma, Texas]]), branded as Chuck E. Cheese Pizzeria & Games. These locations feature more upscale decor with a \"muted\" interior color scheme, an open kitchen, the \"Play Pass\" card system to replace arcade tokens, and the animatronic stage show replaced by a dance floor area. These changes, along with expansions to food offerings, are intended to help the chain provide an experience that can appeal better to adult visitors, and encourage family dining as opposed to primarily parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-chuck-e-cheese-band-breakup-0824-biz-20170823-story.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's breaking up the (animatronic) band|last=Channick|first=Robert|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/09/chuck-e-cheeses-is-getting-a-major-redesign.html|title=Chuck E. Cheese's is getting a major redesign|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|work=[[CNBC]]|date=2017-08-09|access-date=2017-09-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the corporation announced it would go public on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] through a shell company, Leo Holdings Corporation, in which Apollo will still own 51% of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrn.com/casual-dining/chuck-e-cheese-s-plans-merger-public-trading|last=Ruggless|first=Ron|date=April 8, 2019|title=Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s plans merger, public trading|work=[[Nation's Restaurant News]]|access-date=Apr 9, 2019}}</ref> ''Bloomberg''  also reported that after going public, Chuck E. Cheese would no longer have animatronic animals as part of the entertainment.<ref name=\"Bloomberg2019\">https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-08/animatronic-animals-won-t-be-part-of-the-public-chuck-e-cheese?srnd=premium</ref> The proposed merger between CEC Entertainment and LEO Holdings Corporation has been terminated as of July 29, 2019.\n\n==Menu items==\nWhile its primary focus is pizza, Chuck E. Cheese also offers [[Lunch meat|cold-cut]] sandwiches, chicken wings, [[salad bar]]s, appetizers, platters, and desserts. Some stores are also used as test locations which feature new Chuck E. Cheese foods.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nutritional Information|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/menu/nutritional-information.pdf|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PDF|date=January 2009|access-date=2009-05-13}}</ref> Certain Chuck E. Cheese locations also offer beer and wine.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lieberman|first1=Al|last2=Esgate|first2=Patricia|title=The Entertainment Marketing Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ROXOZCJa1kC&pg=PT297|format=PDF|access-date=2009-05-13|edition=Illustrated|year=2002|publisher=FT Press|isbn=0-13-029350-4|page=272|chapter=Location-Based Entertainment and Experiential Branding|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0ROXOZCJa1kC&pg=PT297&lr=#PPT294,M1|last-author-amp=yes}}</ref>\n\nStarting on November 13, 2012, new gluten-free menu items were available at more than 500 locations in the U.S. and Canada. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/new-glutenfree-offerings|title=New Gluten-Free Offerings - Chuck E. Cheese's|work=Chuck E. Cheese}}</ref>\n\n==Arcade and currency==\n\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese (4328479524).jpg|thumb|right|140px|A 2001 Chuck E. Cheese token.]]\nFrom the time of the company's inception to today, one of the main draws for the stores has been the [[Video arcade|arcade]].<ref name=\"fsm\"/><ref name=\"investor\"/> The arcade games primarily consist of either [[redemption game]]s or [[Arcade game|video arcade games]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Games & Rides|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/the-experience/games-rides.php|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc|format=PHP|access-date=2009-05-13}}</ref>\n\nThe brass [[Token coin|tokens]] issued by the company for use in their arcades exist in numerous varieties, and are collected by [[exonumia]] enthusiasts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chuck E. Cheese Tokens|work=Forrest's Token Page|url=http://users.pullman.com/fjstevens/tokens/cec/CEC.html|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>  The company once tested a card access method for use with their arcade and skill games in one location. The test location would no longer use tokens, and instead use a refillable card to access credits, which replace tokens, and points, which replace tickets. However, this was later scrapped. It was tested under different names, including \"Chuck E.'s Super Discount Card\" and \"Chuck E. Token Card\".<ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=CEC Token Cards|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/tokens/cards/index.html|format=CSS|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=Super Discount Card Poster 9Irving, TX 2006)|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/cec/tx_irving_cv3/03.jpg|format=JPG|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref>\nThis method is currently being tested in some markets again. Instead of electronic tickets like the former cards, patrons still carry paper tickets, and the card just takes the place of the metal tokens. CECE, or CEC Entertainment, has called the new system \"Play Pass\".\n\n==Characters==\n[[File:Chuck E. Cheese animatronic, Laguna Hills, CA.jpg |thumb |right |Chuck E. Cheese animatronic, with \"Pizza Time\" clock, in 2017.]]\n\nAlong with the arcade, the other main draw for the centers since the beginning was its animatronic show.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loftus |first1=Jamie |title=A History of Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Animatronic Band |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kkn7y/a-history-of-chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band |website=Vice |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> However, there are now several different styles of animatronic shows in use within the company, depending on when the location opened, whether it was renovated, and other factors.<ref>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Travis|title=Pizza Time Theatre: Stage Shows|work=Showbiz Pizza.com|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/ptp/stages/index.html|format=CSS|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>\n\nWhen the first location opened in 1977, the animatronic characters were featured in framed portraits hanging on the walls of the main dining area, but they are no longer in use today. The original show featured Crusty The Cat (the first character to face retirement as he was soon replaced with Mr. Munch in 1978), Pasqually the singing chef, Jasper T. Jowls, the Warblettes, and the main focus of the show, Chuck E. Cheese.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Program|publisher=[[Atari]]|year=1977|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/promo/ptt/ptt_77menu.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> In the early 90s, when the franchise unified Chuck E. Cheese with ShowBiz Pizza, the animatronics used for [[the Rock-afire Explosion]] band were redressed as \"Munch's Make Believe Band\", with Chuck E., Jasper, Helen Henny, Munch, and Pasqually costumes replacing the Rock-afire characters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Loftus |first1=Jamie |title=A History of Chuck E. Cheese\u2019s Animatronic Band |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9kkn7y/a-history-of-chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Vice |date=August 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater, restaurants also added \"Cabaret\" shows in separate rooms of each restaurant.<ref name=\"fsm\"/> One of the early Cabaret characters was Dolli Dimples, a hippopotamus who played the piano and sang in the blues/jazz style of performer [[Pearl Bailey]].<ref name=infoworld/>\n\nThe in-house control system consisted of a [[MOS Technology 6502|6502]]-based controller in a card cage with various driver boards was called \"Cyberamics\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Balcony Show Photograph #1|year=1981|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/ptt/fl_brandon/10.jpg|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Time Theatre Balcony Show Photograph #2|date=1980s|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/photos/ptt/nm_unknown/05.jpg|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1998, the company's show installed into new stores, referred to as \"Studio C\", consisted of a single animated Chuck E. Cheese character created by [[Garner Holt]] alongside large television monitors, lighting effects, and interactive elements.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Chuck E.'s New Look|publisher=Garner Holt Productions|year=1998|format=PDF|url=http://www.showbizpizza.com/info/articles/cec/cec_98studioc.pdf|access-date=2009-03-03}}</ref> The other characters appear as puppets on the TV screens. The control system dubbed \"Cyberstar\" was re-designed from the ground up and produced by Dave Philipsen. In some markets, the company has also tried a new store concept that omits the animated show entirely. This is the Circle of Lights stage which either consists of a live Chuck E. Cheese costume character or an animatronic in a futuristic light stage with large television monitors. \n\nIn July 2012, the longstanding rat mascot was rebranded, changing to a slimmer rock star mouse who plays electric guitar. Voice actor [[Duncan Brannan]], who for 19 years had characterized Chuck E. Cheese as a wise-cracking rat from New Jersey, was replaced with [[Jaret Reddick]], the frontman and guitarist for the pop punk band [[Bowling for Soup]].<ref name=\"AP 2012\"/><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/chuck-e-cheese-makeover-duncan-brannan-jaret-reddick-344677</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the chain announced that animatronic shows would be removed in favor of a modernized dance floor. The move was piloted in a handful of locations prior to being implemented company-wide.<ref name=\"AnimatronicRemoval\">{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Jennings|title=Chuck E. Cheese's Animatronic Band Is Starting to Break Up and Fans Are Heartbroken|url=https://gizmodo.com/chuck-e-cheeses-animatronic-band-is-starting-to-break-1797875869|access-date=18 August 2017|work=GizModo|publisher=GizModo|date=17 August 2017}}</ref> <ref name=\"AnimatronicRemoval\" /> The characters were removed from all chains in November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Chuck E. Cheese unveils new restaurant design, gets rid of tokens |url=https://abc7chicago.com/business/chuck-e-cheese-unveils-new-restaurant-design/5691942/ |accessdate=5 March 2020 |publisher=ABC7 Chicago |date=Nov 12, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:CEC 32.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Chuck E. Cheese [[walkaround character]] performing in 2017.]]\n\n===Costumed shows===\nTwo types of costumed shows are used by Chuck E. Cheese: the Live show and the Road show. The Live show is performed at the front of the stage in the showroom, whenever a child is celebrating a birthday. In the live show a customized rendition of \"Happy Birthday\" is sung to the child that is celebrating the birthday. A costumed Chuck E. Cheese dances with the guests and sings, while being accompanied by the cast members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Birthday Parties|work=Chuck E. Cheese Official Site|publisher=CEC Entertainment, Inc.|url=http://www.chuckecheese.com/parties/birthday.php|format=PHP|access-date=2009-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228204107/http://www.chuckecheese.com/parties/birthday.php|archive-date=2009-02-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Road show is a performance by a costumed Chuck E. Cheese character, and is performed outside the normal showroom. Children are gathered via the public announcement system or by Chuck E. Cheese himself.  The children must dance in order to win free tickets. The free tickets are thrown at the end of the performance for all the children that participated. Chuck comes out every hour on the half hour. The songs that he and the children dance to are usually well-known classic songs such as \"[[If You're Happy and You Know It]]\" and \"[[Head, Shoulders, Knees, and Toes]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chuck E. Cheeses}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.chuckecheese.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Companies|Food}}\n{{Pizza chains|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Irving, Texas]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of Canada]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pizza franchises]]\n[[Category:Video arcades]]\n[[Category:Fictional mice and rats]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1984]]\n[[Category:Theme restaurants]]\n[[Category:Animatronic attractions]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1980s fads and trends]]\n[[Category:Fast-food franchises]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1977]]\n[[Category:2014 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Apollo Global Management companies]]\n[[Category:1977 in robotics]]\n[[Category:Atari]]\n", "name_user": "69.117.218.5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chuck_E._Cheese"}
{"title_page": "Flight Log", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Flight Log (1966-1976)\n| type       = greatest\n| artist     = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| cover      = JA_Flight-Log.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 7, 1977\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]], [[psychedelic rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Grunt Records|Grunt]]/[[RCA Records]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| prev_title = [[Early Flight]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[2400 Fulton Street]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Jefferson Starship]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title = [[Spitfire (Jefferson Starship album)|Spitfire]]\n | prev_year  = 1976\n | title      = Flight Log\n | year       = 1977\n | next_title = [[Earth (Jefferson Starship album)|Earth]]\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Hot Tuna]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title = [[Hoppkorv]]\n | prev_year  = 1976\n | title      = Flight Log\n | year       = 1977\n | next_title = [[Double Dose (Hot Tuna album)|Double Dose]]\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = greatest\n | cover   = JA_Flight_Log_Obi.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Japanese re-release\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r41727 |title=Flight Log (1966-1976) - Jefferson Airplane &#124; AllMusic |first=J.P. |last=Ollio |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011|archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev2Score = C+<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Jefferson+Starship |title=Robert Christgau: CG: Jefferson Starship |first=Robert |last=Christgau |work=robertchristgau.com |year=2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606155926/http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Jefferson+Starship |archive-date=June 6, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Flight Log (1966\u20131976)''''' is a compilation album by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Jefferson Airplane]]. Released in January 1977 as a double-LP as Grunt CYL2-1255, it is a compilation of Jefferson Airplane and Airplane-related tracks, including tracks by [[Jefferson Starship]] and [[Hot Tuna]], as well as solo tracks by [[Paul Kantner]], [[Grace Slick]], and [[Jorma Kaukonen]]. Although primarily a compilation album, the album includes one previously unreleased song: \"Please Come Back\" written by [[Ron Nagle]] and performed by Jefferson Starship.  \"Please Come Back\" is not available on any other release.\n\nAmong the session musicians featured on the album are two members of the [[Grateful Dead]] and one member of [[Crosby, Stills & Nash|Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]].  David Crosby appears on one track, and [[Jerry Garcia]] plays on three tracks, two of which also feature [[Mickey Hart]].\n\nThe album included a lavish 12-page full-color, full-size (12 sq.in.) booklet, containing photographs of the band throughout the period covered by the compilation. It also contained a detailed history of the band, written by Patrick Snyder of [[Rolling Stone]] magazine.\n\n''Flight Log'' was first reissued on CD by BMG Japan on October 22, 2008 as a part of the \"Paper Sleeve Collection\" reissue series (BVCM-35468-9). The release features an exact reproduction of the Grunt 1977 edition of the LP packaging including a reduced scale reproduction of the original booklet and inner sleeve jackets for the CDs.  Also included is a second booklet containing all the lyrics in both English and Japanese. The only omission by BMG Japan was not reproducing the original GRUNT label on the CDs. The audio quality is as good as the original master tapes available for the Japanese LP pressing and features JVC K2 24 Bit Remastering. However, it sounds as if the master tapes had been damaged on at least three songs, and significantly obvious on the introduction of \"Silver Spoon\". CD 1 contains Side A and B, and CD 2 contains Side C and D.\n\nOn April 5, 2011, BGO Records released a remastered edition of Flight Log in a standard jewel case with cardboard slip cover. The BGO version is said to be a sonic improvement on the BMG/Sony edition, nonetheless, certain tape defects such as on Silver Spoon still exist.\n\n==Track listing (with artist)==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side A\n| title1          = Come Up the Years\n| note1           = from ''[[Jefferson Airplane Takes Off]]''\n| writer1         = [[Marty Balin]], [[Paul Kantner]]\n| extra1          = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| length1         = 2:30\n| title2          = [[White Rabbit (song)|White Rabbit]]\n| note2           = from ''[[Surrealistic Pillow]]''\n| writer2         = [[Grace Slick]]\n| extra2          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length2         = 2:27\n| title3          = [[Comin' Back to Me]]\n| note3           = from ''Surrealistic Pillow''\n| writer3         = Balin \n| extra3          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length3         = 5:15\n| title4          = Won't You Try / Saturday Afternoon\n| note4           = from ''[[After Bathing at Baxter's]]''\n| writer4         = Kantner\n| extra4          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length4         = 5:02\n| title5          = Greasy Heart\n| note5           = from ''[[Crown of Creation]]''\n| writer5         = Slick\n| extra5          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length5         = 3:25\n| title6          = If You Feel\n| note6           = from ''Crown of Creation''\n| writer6         = Balin, Gary Blackman\n| extra6          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length6         = 3:30\n\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side B\n| title1          = [[Somebody to Love (Jefferson Airplane song)|Somebody to Love]]\n| note1           = live, from ''[[Bless Its Pointed Little Head]]''\n| writer1         = Darby Slick\n| extra1          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length1         = 3:46\n| title2          = [[Wooden Ships]]\n| note2           = from ''[[Volunteers (Jefferson Airplane album)|Volunteers]]''\n| writer2         = [[David Crosby]], Kantner, [[Stephen Stills]]\n| extra2          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length2         = 6:00\n| title3          = [[Volunteers (song)|Volunteers]]\n| note3           = from ''Volunteers''\n| writer3         = Balin, Kantner\n| extra3          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length3         = 2:03\n| title4          = Hesitation Blues\n| note4           = from ''[[Hot Tuna (album)|Hot Tuna]]''\n| writer4         = traditional, arranged by [[Jorma Kaukonen]], [[Jack Casady]]\n| extra4          = [[Hot Tuna]]\n| length4         = 5:05\n| title5          = Have You Seen the Stars Tonite?\n| note5           = from ''[[Blows Against the Empire]]''\n| writer5         = Crosby, Kantner\n| extra5          = [[Paul Kantner]], [[Jefferson Starship]]\n| length5         = 3:42\n\n}}\n  \t\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side C\n| title1          = Silver Spoon\n| note1           = from ''[[Sunfighter]]''\n| writer1         = Slick\n| extra1          = Paul Kantner, [[Grace Slick]]\n| length1         = 5:40\n| title2          = Feel So Good\n| note2           = from ''[[Bark (Jefferson Airplane album)|Bark]]''\n| writer2         = Kaukonen\n| extra2          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length2         = 4:35\n| title3          = Pretty as You Feel\n| note3           = single version A-side Grunt #65-0500, from ''Bark''\n| writer3         = [[Joey Covington]], Casady, Kaukonen\n| extra3          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length3         = 3:07\n| title4          = Milk Train\n| note4           = from ''[[Long John Silver (album)|Long John Silver]]''\n| writer4         = Slick, [[Papa John Creach]], Roger Spotts\n| extra4          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length4         = 3:26\n| title5          = [[Ja-Da|Ja Da]] (Keep on Truckin')\n| note5           = from ''[[Burgers (album)|Burgers]]''\n| writer5         = Bob Carleton\n| extra5          = Hot Tuna\n| length5         = 3:40\n\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side D\n| title1          = \u00bfCome Again Toucan?\n| note1           = from ''[[Manhole (album)|Manhole]]''\n| writer1         = [[David Freiberg]], Slick\n| extra1          = Grace Slick\n| length1         = 3:13\n| title2          = Sketches of China\n| note2           = from ''[[Baron von Tollbooth & the Chrome Nun]]''\n| writer2         = Kantner, Slick\n| extra2          = Paul Kantner, Grace Slick, [[David Freiberg]]\n| length2         = 5:13\n| title3          = Genesis\n| note3           = from ''[[Quah (album)|Quah]]''\n| writer3         = Kaukonen\n| extra3          = [[Jorma Kaukonen]]\n| length3         = 4:19\n| title4          = Ride the Tiger\n| note4           = from ''[[Dragon Fly (album)|Dragon Fly]]''\n| writer4         = Kantner, Slick, Byong Yu\n| extra4          = Grace Slick, Paul Kantner, Jefferson Starship\n| length4         = 5:06\n| title5          = Please Come Back\n| note5           = live\n| writer5         = [[Ron Nagle]]\n| extra5          = Jefferson Starship\n| length5         = 4:02\n\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n[[File:Jefferson airplane 1977.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Photo for ''Flight Log'' album ad, 1977. From left: Grace Slick, Marty Balin, Jorma Kaukonen, Paul Kantner, Jack Casady, Spencer Dryden.]]\n\n*[[Signe Anderson]] \u2013 vocals\n*[[Marty Balin]] \u2013 vocals\n*[[Skip Spence]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Paul Kantner]] \u2013 vocals, rhythm guitar\n*[[Jorma Kaukonen]] \u2013 lead guitar, acoustic guitar, vocals\n*[[Jack Casady]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Grace Slick]] \u2013 vocals, piano\n*[[Spencer Dryden]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Jerry Garcia]] \u2013 guitar, pedal steel guitar, lead guitar\n*[[Nicky Hopkins]] \u2013 piano\n*Will Scarlett \u2013 harmonica\n*[[David Crosby]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n*[[Mickey Hart]] \u2013 percussion, gongs\n*[[Joey Covington]] \u2013 drums, vocals\n*[[Papa John Creach]] \u2013 violin\n*[[John Barbata]] \u2013 drums\n*Sammy Piazza \u2013 drums\n*Nick Buck \u2013 piano\n*[[David Freiberg]] \u2013 vocals, keyboards, bass, rhythm guitar\n*[[Craig Chaquico]] \u2013 lead guitar\n*[[Jack Traylor]] \u2013 vocals\n*[[Chris Ethridge]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Tom Hobson]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[Pete Sears]] \u2013 bass, rhythm guitar\nThree of the tracks have contributions from members of the [[Grateful Dead]].\n\n===Production===\n*Bill Thompson \u2013 manager\n*Jacky Kaukonen \u2013 secretary\n*Bill Laudner \u2013 road manager\n*Pat Ieraci (Maurice) \u2013 production coordinator, album coordinator\n*Paul Dowell \u2013 equipment manager\n*Roger Ressmeyer, Tony Lane, Jim Marshall, Dave Patrick, B. Beckhard, Jim Smircich, Charles Stewart, Randy Tuten \u2013 photography\n*Mastered by John Golden, Kendun Recorders, Burbank\n*Craig DeCamps \u2013 booklet design\n*Acy R. Lehman \u2013 cover and art direction\n*Takuya Matsuyama \u2013 product director for Japanese release\n*Asami Konno \u2013 creative coordinator for Japanese release\n*Kazuhisa Fujita \u2013 design for Japanese release\n*STRANGE DAYS \u2013 support for Japanese release\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite AV media notes |title=Flight Log |others=[[Jefferson Airplane]] |year=1977 |type=Vinyl booklet|publisher=[[Grunt Records]] |id=CYL2-1255 |location=[[San Francisco]] }}\n\n{{Jefferson Airplane}}\n{{Hot Tuna}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flight Log (Album)}}\n[[Category:1977 greatest hits albums]]\n[[Category:Hot Tuna compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Jefferson Airplane compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Jefferson Starship albums]]\n[[Category:Split albums]]\n[[Category:Grunt Records compilation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Flight Log (1966-1976)\n| type       = greatest\n| artist     = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| cover      = JA_Flight-Log.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = January 7, 1977\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]], [[psychedelic rock]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Grunt Records|Grunt]]/[[RCA Records]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| prev_title = [[Early Flight]]\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[2400 Fulton Street]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Jefferson Starship]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title = [[Spitfire (Jefferson Starship album)|Spitfire]]\n | prev_year  = 1976\n | title      = Flight Log\n | year       = 1977\n | next_title = [[Earth (Jefferson Starship album)|Earth]]\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Hot Tuna]]\n | type       = greatest\n | prev_title = [[Hoppkorv]]\n | prev_year  = 1976\n | title      = Flight Log\n | year       = 1977\n | next_title = [[Double Dose (Hot Tuna album)|Double Dose]]\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = greatest\n | cover   = JA_Flight_Log_Obi.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Japanese re-release\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/r41727 |title=Flight Log (1966-1976) - Jefferson Airplane &#124; AllMusic |first=J.P. |last=Ollio |work=allmusic.com |year=2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011|archive-url= |archive-date= |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev2Score = C+<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Jefferson+Starship |title=Robert Christgau: CG: Jefferson Starship |first=Robert |last=Christgau |work=robertchristgau.com |year=2011 |accessdate=9 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606155926/http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=Jefferson+Starship |archive-date=June 6, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Flight Log (1966\u20131976)''''' is a compilation album by the American [[rock music|rock]] band [[Jefferson Airplane]]. Released in January 1977 as a double-LP as Grunt CYL2-1255, it is a compilation of Jefferson Airplane and Airplane-related tracks, including tracks by [[Jefferson Starship]] and [[Hot Tuna]], as well as solo tracks by [[Paul Kantner]], [[Grace Slick]], and [[Jorma Kaukonen]]. Although primarily a compilation album, the album includes one previously unreleased song: \"Please Come Back\" written by [[Ron Nagle]] and performed by Jefferson Starship.  \"Please Come Back\" is not available on any other release.\n\nAmong the session musicians featured on the album are two members of the [[Grateful Dead]] and one member of [[Crosby, Stills & Nash|Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]].  David Crosby appears on one track, and [[Jerry Garcia]] plays on three tracks, two of which also feature [[Mickey Hart]].\n\nThe album included a lavish 12-page full-color, full-size (12 sq.in.) booklet, containing photographs of the band throughout the period covered by the compilation. It also contained a detailed history of the band, written by Patrick Snyder of [[Rolling Stone]] magazine.\n\n''Flight Log'' was first reissued on CD by BMG Japan on October 22, 2008 as a part of the \"Paper Sleeve Collection\" reissue series (BVCM-35468-9). The release features an exact reproduction of the Grunt 1977 edition of the LP packaging including a reduced scale reproduction of the original booklet and inner sleeve jackets for the CDs.  Also included is a second booklet containing all the lyrics in both English and Japanese. The only omission by BMG Japan was not reproducing the original GRUNT label on the CDs. The audio quality is as good as the original master tapes available for the Japanese LP pressing and features JVC K2 24 Bit Remastering. However, it sounds as if the master tapes had been damaged on at least three songs, and significantly obvious on the introduction of \"Silver Spoon\". CD 1 contains Side A and B, and CD 2 contains Side C and D.\n\nOn April 5, 2011, BGO Records released a remastered edition of Flight Log in a standard jewel case with cardboard slip cover. The BGO version is said to be a sonic improvement on the BMG/Sony edition, nonetheless, certain tape defects such as on Silver Spoon still exist.\n\n==Track listing (with artist)==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side A\n| title1          = Come Up the Years\n| note1           = from ''[[Jefferson Airplane Takes Off]]''\n| writer1         = [[Marty Balin]], [[Paul Kantner]]\n| extra1          = [[Jefferson Airplane]]\n| length1         = 2:30\n| title2          = [[White Rabbit (song)|White Rabbit]]\n| note2           = from ''[[Surrealistic Pillow]]''\n| writer2         = [[Grace Slick]]\n| extra2          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length2         = 2:27\n| title3          = [[Comin' Back to Me]]\n| note3           = from ''Surrealistic Pillow''\n| writer3         = Balin \n| extra3          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length3         = 5:15\n| title4          = Won't You Try / Saturday Afternoon\n| note4           = from ''[[After Bathing at Baxter's]]''\n| writer4         = Kantner\n| extra4          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length4         = 5:02\n| title5          = Greasy Heart\n| note5           = from ''[[Crown of Creation]]''\n| writer5         = Slick\n| extra5          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length5         = 3:25\n| title6          = If You Feel\n| note6           = from ''Crown of Creation''\n| writer6         = Balin, Gary Blackman\n| extra6          = Jefferson Airplane\n| length6         = 3:30\n\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Artist\n| headline        = Side B\n| title1          = [[Somebody to Love (Jefferson Airplane song)|Somebody to Love]]\n| note1           = live, from ''[[Bless Its Pointed Little Head]]''\n| writer1         = Darby Slick\n| extra1          = Jefferson Airpla